The Senate has said the only way the Petroleum Industry Bill will get Presidential assent is for the executive and the National Assembly to produce a single document that will address the challenges in the oil sector.  President of the Senate, Ahmad Lawan, who stated this on Thursday, during the screening of one of the 43 ministerial nominees, Senator Tayo Alasoadura, at plenary stressed the need to harmonize the PIB which has been repeatedly refused assent by the executive since 1999. During the screening exercise, Senator Alasoadura had appealed to the Senate to revisit the PIB which was broken down to four parts by the 8th assembly for the good of Nigerians  He also urged the senate to fast-rack the passage of Nigeria Nuclear Regulatory Bill adding that the World has moved from crude oil to clean energy.  Major General (RTD) Bashir Magashi, during his screening, harped on the need to improve the welfare of the Nigerian troops.  Our Senate Correspondent, Raliat Adenekan said other Ministerial Nominees screened today are : Timipire Sylva, Mustapha Baba, Ramatu Tijani Aliyu, Abubakar Aliyu, Ambassador Zubairu Dada, Otunba Adeniyi Adebayo, Mohammed H. Abdullahi, Sunday Akin Dare, Doctor Chris Ngige. The Upper chamber is expected to hold an extraordinary plenary tomorrow to continue the screening of ministerial nominees.